Here are both approaches for navigating from `ProductListPage` to `ProductDetailsPage`:

## 1. Register the Route (AppShell.xaml.cs)

```csharp
public partial class AppShell : Shell
{
    public AppShell()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
    }
}
```

## 2. Navigate from ProductListPage

**Approach A â€” String ID via query string:**

```csharp
// In ProductListViewModel or code-behind
async void OnProductTapped(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

**Approach B â€” Full object via `ShellNavigationQueryParameters`:**

```csharp
async void OnProductTapped(Product product)
{
    var parameters = new ShellNavigationQueryParameters
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
}
```

## 3. Receive Data with IQueryAttributable on the ViewModel

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private string _productId;
    private Product _product;

    public string ProductId
    {
        get => _productId;
        set => SetProperty(ref _productId, value);
    }

    public Product Product
    {
        get => _product;
        set => SetProperty(ref _product, value);
    }

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A: receive the string ID
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
        {
            ProductId = id.ToString();
            // Load full product from a service, DB, etc.
        }

        // Approach B: receive the full object
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
        {
            Product = p;
            ProductId = p.Id;
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Differences

| | Query String | ShellNavigationQueryParameters |
|---|---|---|
| **Data type** | Strings only | Any object |
| **Serialization** | Values become URL-encoded strings | Passed by reference, no serialization |
| **Use case** | Simple IDs, flags | Complex objects, collections |
| **Deep-link friendly** | Yes | No |

Both approaches call `ApplyQueryAttributes` on the ViewModel automatically â€” as long as the ViewModel implements `IQueryAttributable` and is set as the page's `BindingContext`.
